WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.060
I'm Garrett Grohlman, a professional educator at RStudio and the author of two books on

00:00:10.060 --> 00:00:14.560
R. I've put together these videos to teach you some of the main ideas of doing data wrangling

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:19.120
with R and the Tidyverse. If you're not familiar with the Tidyverse, it's a collection of R

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:24.200
packages that are designed to help you do data science.

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:27.719
In this series of short videos, we will walk through some of the most useful tools for

00:00:27.719 --> 00:00:33.119
wrangling your data with R. Also keep in mind that you can skip around these videos

00:00:33.119 --> 00:00:40.360
to the tool that you want by clicking the jump to links in the video description.

00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:44.240
So there's one last thing that you will probably want to do as you wrangle your data with these

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:50.439
packages and that's combine multiple datasets into the same dataset. There's a simple way

00:00:50.439 --> 00:00:55.720
to combine datasets together in R. If your datasets were meant to go together, you can

00:00:55.720 --> 00:01:00.360
add them together by pasting one as extra columns onto the first with the bind calls

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:05.120
command from dplyr. There's also a cbind command in base R. Bind calls is just a little more

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:10.519
optimized. So that's why I'm showing you bind calls.

00:01:10.519 --> 00:01:14.680
This is somewhat dangerous to do. R has no way of checking whether the rows are in the

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:19.760
same order between the datasets or whether when you combine the datasets together, the

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:26.199
row describes an observation that makes sense. For example, here you probably want B to be

00:01:26.199 --> 00:01:30.879
on the second line as in the first line. So use column binding with caution. Make sure

00:01:30.879 --> 00:01:34.239
the data is arranged for you to do what you want to do.

00:01:34.239 --> 00:01:38.839
You can add the second dataset as additional rows to the bottom of your first dataset with

00:01:38.839 --> 00:01:43.919
bind rows or rbind in base R. Again, you need to make sure that the variables are in the

00:01:43.919 --> 00:01:49.519
same order and mean the same thing, but it's probably less risky than column binding.

00:01:49.519 --> 00:01:52.720
Even if you actually have two datasets like this where they describe the same variables,

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:57.120
they just have different observations of those variables, you could actually use set operations

00:01:57.120 --> 00:02:04.160
on these datasets. So data frame set operations come with dplyr. You take two data frames

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:09.199
and get the union of rows that appear in both data frames, the intersection of rows that

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:14.080
appear in both data frames, and the set difference of rows that appear in both data frames. That's

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:19.919
just your basic union intersection set different things applied to data frames.

00:02:19.919 --> 00:02:22.520
Now normally when you want to put datasets together, you need to do something a little

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:28.000
more involved, and that's what I call joining data. So here's a trivial example. Here's

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.800
two data frames. They both talk about the Beatles. One's a list of songs and who wrote

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:37.119
each of the songs, and then one's a list of the artists in the Beatles and what each one

00:02:37.119 --> 00:02:41.320
played or one of the instruments they played. And if you wanted to put these things together

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:46.880
into the same dataset, so you match up the instrument that each Beatle played with, you

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:52.759
know, what song they wrote, you can do that with a left join. What left join does is it

00:02:52.759 --> 00:02:57.240
takes the names of two data frames, and then it takes some joining criteria. These would

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:02.520
be the name or names of columns that both datasets share. And then what it will do is

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:08.880
it'll go through the second data frame, find the pieces of information that apply to rows

00:03:08.919 --> 00:03:13.279
in the first data frame, and add them where they belong in that data frame. So order is

00:03:13.279 --> 00:03:16.960
not preserved. The second data frame's order is not preserved. First data frame, yes, that

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:21.759
is preserved. But things are moved around to supply a play column that actually makes

00:03:21.759 --> 00:03:27.679
sense with your data frame. And at the end, you have rows in your output that describe

00:03:27.679 --> 00:03:33.360
a unified observation. John both wrote Across the Universe and played guitar. Guitar had

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:38.360
to appear twice because John was also in the second row, and so it appears twice. There's

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:42.880
no information about this last row, Buddy Holly, who made Peggy Sue. So for the place

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:48.320
column that gets an NA, there's nothing we could put there. Left joins aren't the only

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:55.520
way to join data together in an intelligent fashion. You could do a right join. Well,

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:59.160
this would be the syntax for if you want to join based on two columns, both first and

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:12.839
last. Use the C to make a vector of column names and pass that to by. That's left join.

00:04:12.839 --> 00:04:16.359
Left join isn't the only way to join data sets together. You could do an inner join,

00:04:16.359 --> 00:04:20.399
which is a little more exclusive. So an inner join still puts the data sets together in

00:04:20.399 --> 00:04:25.079
the same fashion, but if there's any row from the first data frame that doesn't have information

00:04:25.079 --> 00:04:28.440
in the second data frame, like Peggy Sue and Buddy Holly didn't appear in the second

00:04:28.440 --> 00:04:33.480
data frame, inner join will exclude that from the results. It just contains the rows that

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:46.200
appeared in both data frames. Then, let me come back to this. Oh, yeah. I'm sorry. So

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:49.799
we just released two new joins in the slides. You'll find them on the cheat sheet. Those

00:04:49.799 --> 00:04:57.359
are right join and outer join. So right join is like a left join, but it has the same effect

00:04:57.359 --> 00:05:02.399
as if you switch the order the data frames appear. If you put artist first and song second,

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:06.399
that would give you the equivalent of a right join. The second data frames prioritize are

00:05:06.399 --> 00:05:11.959
the first. An outer join is the complement of an inner join. An inner join only keeps

00:05:11.959 --> 00:05:15.640
the rows that appear in both data frames. An outer join keeps every row that appears

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:19.399
in any data frame, and you get a very big data frame at the end, but that probably has

00:05:19.399 --> 00:05:25.079
a bunch of missing values. You could look those up on the cheat sheet. Then we have

00:05:25.079 --> 00:05:29.600
two filtering joins, semi-join and anti-join. These don't actually join data sets together

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:35.040
at all. These take the first data set and remove rows from it based on what appears

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:39.160
in the second data set. So what semi-join will do is it'll take the first data set,

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:44.239
look at the data set and see which rows have an equivalent in the second data set and return

00:05:44.440 --> 00:05:47.559
just those rows that have an equivalent. It doesn't add anything to the rows, it just

00:05:47.559 --> 00:05:53.200
shows you what rows will actually be joined should you do a join. Anti does the opposite.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:57.559
It shows you which rows do not have equivalent in the second data set. So you can use anti-join

00:05:57.559 --> 00:06:01.600
to see which rows will not be joined when you do a join. Semi-join and anti-join are

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:08.600
good ways to sort of debug or get a feel for how the join's going to work ahead of time.

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:15.600
All right. So let's skip over some of this recap. We're getting near the top of the hour

00:06:16.359 --> 00:06:20.720
so I just want to point your attention to where you can learn more. This cheat sheet

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:24.760
is a really great and concise way to go about learning how to wrangle data with these two

00:06:24.760 --> 00:06:28.799
packages. You can download it here at this link. We also have other cheat sheets about

00:06:28.799 --> 00:06:34.440
other things there. If you want to practice with dplyr, there's a course that I've made

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:39.000
with Datacamp that has about four hours worth of content on dplyr. There's some video lessons,

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:43.519
it's a live coding environment, and mostly it has lots and lots of practice. So this

00:06:43.519 --> 00:06:48.519
is a good place to go if you want to practice. It does cost, I think, $95 or so.

00:06:48.519 --> 00:06:52.839
Thanks for checking out our data wrangling video series. This is just one video in a

00:06:52.839 --> 00:06:57.040
larger set of resources on data wrangling. So here are links to all of our other videos

00:06:57.040 --> 00:07:01.839
in the series. And again, have a look at the video description for shortcuts to other parts

00:07:01.839 --> 00:07:06.239
of the series, as well as other resources we think might be helpful, like cheat sheets

00:07:06.239 --> 00:07:10.799
and further documentation. We hope you find all of these resources useful, and if you

00:07:10.799 --> 00:07:15.880
do, as always, we would appreciate a thumbs up or a share. Both go a long way to helping

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:19.440
this content reach people who could benefit from it.

